         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">2[3]/2/67 ¶  ¶ It gave me great pleasure, dear Mr Bentham, to receive your very kind letter of the 19 Dec &amp; the finishing proofsheets of the 3. vol. ¶  I admire much your arrangement &amp; methodical trea...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">67.02.23</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, ff. 256-7.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">2[3]/2/67</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It gave me great pleasure, dear Mr Bentham, to receive your very kind letter of the 19 Dec &amp; the finishing proofsheets of the 3. vol.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">Bentham (1863-78), vol. 3.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> I admire much your arrangement &amp; methodical treatment of so much difficult material &amp; you have placed by your great researches in this volume your claims on scientific acknowledgement still higher</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have freely given you my opinions on some points; requiring still extended consideration. The Diagnosis of Langes <name key="Erechtites%20Muelleri">Erechtites Muelleri</name> I enclose.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Lange (1861), pp. 28-9.</p>
               </note> An unfortunate renaming of <name key="Diplanthera%20tetraphylla">Diplanthera tetraphylla</name> has taken place (for similar causes as led to the establishing of <name key="Argyrodendron">Argyrodendron</name>).<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M erected <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Argyrodendron">Argyrodendron</name>
                     </seg> (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">A. trifoliatum</seg>) in B58.03.01, p. 2; Bentham (1863-78), vol. 1, p. 231, regognised it as a species of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Tarrietia</seg>.</p>
               </note> RBr in placing the genus in <name key="Scrophularinae">Scrophularinae</name> has misled us all. It is strange that he should not have remembered this peculiar form of Anthers in so many bignoniaceae. I thus only <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">accidentally</hi>
               </seg> recognized the indentity of <name key="Bulweria%20nobilissima">Bulweria nobilissima</name> &amp; <name key="Diplanthera%20tetraphylla">Diplanthera tetraphylla</name>. The genus <name key="Deplanchea">Deplanchea</name>, as Seeman has pointed out, belongs seemingly also to this genus.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M erected <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Bulweria</seg> (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">B. nobilissima</seg>) in B64.11.01, p. 147. Bentham (1863-78), vol. 4, p. 541 treats it, and M's <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Deplanchea">Deplanchea</name> bulwerii</seg> (B65.10.04, p. 72), as synonyms of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Diplanthera%20tetraphylla">Diplanthera tetraphylla</name>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="">, described in R. Brown (1810), p. 449.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> I have Panchers specimens &amp; will carefully analyze them. At present I am still among Goodeniaceae, the Exhibition duties absorbing most of my time, but this very day it <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">closes</hi>
               </seg> after 1[6] months engagements,<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">Intercolonial Exhibition of Australasia, Melbourne, 1866-7.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> and altho' more particularly on my recommendation an industrial Museum will arise out of it, yet I hope I can work on that at leisure, if I undertake in it the administration of the phytological branch. The "Kent" sails in the middle of next week. If not by her I will send the rest of the Goodeniaceae &amp;c by next clipper. I have forwarded some and the <name key="Lobeliaceae">Lobeliaceae</name> by the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Great Britain</hi>
               </seg>.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Great Britain </seg>sailed on 25 January 1867. The next box was not sent on <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Kent</seg>, but was sent on <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Wellesley</seg> on 1 April 1867. (RB MSS M44, Notebook recording despatch of plants for Bentham for <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Flora australiensis</seg>, Library, RBG Melbourne).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Of the limits of the genera of <name key="Angiantheae">Angiantheae</name> we shall still get a better knowledge by additional <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">interior</hi>
               </seg> explorations, as many of these little annuals are evidently as yet overlooked. Indeed many of these are only during the winter rains to be had; hence travellers may often pass over districts with new forms of these &amp; never get the plants, even if eager for them. They evidently constitute a fe[a]ture in the flora of Central Australia.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>What are your views on the elaboration of the Acotyledonous plants? The filices are easy of examination and the <name key="Algae%20">Algae </name>are extant in poor Harveys superb work;<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">Harvey (1858-63).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> but what is to be done with <name key="Lichens">Lichens</name>, <name key="Lichenastra">Lichenastra</name>, <name key="Musci">Musci</name>, <name key="Fungi">Fungi</name>, <name key="Characeae">Characeae</name>? It would be well to come to some timely arrangement on the subject &amp; to entrust the task to safe conservative workers.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Rev. Mr Berkeley <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">might</hi>
               </seg> be able to find time for fungi, but it appears to me very doubtful; I intend, if providence grants me health, to study these plants for a summer in our ranges. My own cryptogamic material is much scattered in continental collections. Still there is a good deal here &amp; at Kew.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You will find RBr's <name key="Monopetaleae">Monopetaleae</name> doubled &amp; tripled</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am looking forward with <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">deep</hi>
               </seg> interest to the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">genera</hi>
               </seg> plantarum.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83). vol. 1, part 3, was expected later in the year.</p>
               </note> Indeed I hope you will for the sake of the Australian plants not let that far more important work come into arrear.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have pointed out the best characters of <name key="Oenanthe">Oenanthe</name> and proved its existence in Australia.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B66.12.03, p. 182.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have done to a small extent for the Exhibition what you desire for generalisation of Australian vegetation,<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B67.13.02; see G. Bentham to M, 19 December 1866.</p>
               </note> but in an exhaustive manner I will do it at the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">close</hi>
               </seg> of your volumes, &amp; combine a special little work with phytographic maps.<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M did not publish an exhaustive outline of the vegetation as a separate volume, but see B86.13.22, at the end of which there is a note 'Abridged from an ampler Paper contributed by Baron von Mueller, K.C.M.G., M.&amp;Ph.D., F.R.S.—E<seg style="font-variant: small-caps; ">d</seg>.'</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Your regardful </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd Mueller</p>
